{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded from the recommendation results regardless of their relevance score.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between inventory-availability filtering and ranking output (MOCK-MISS). A unit test of only scoring or only filtering can miss regressions where ranked items bypass stock filtering. No real OS/network/subprocess is required by this behavior text, and no AI/ML output-quality dependency is stated, so System/Agentic are rejected.","test_description":"Wire recommender service with real in-process modules (catalog repo fixture + availability filter + ranker) and assert an out-of-stock high-score product never appears in returned recommendations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The user preference filter correctly excludes product categories the user has explicitly blocked in their settings.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Bug appears at module boundary: user-settings retrieval/representation must be applied by category filter (MOCK-MISS). Pure unit logic on a filter function may miss mapping/serialization mismatches from settings module. Behavior does not require real OS/network/subprocess or model judgment, so System/Agentic are disqualified.","test_description":"Run recommendation request with in-process user-settings store fixture containing blocked categories and verify returned list excludes all products from those categories.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The recommendation algorithm ranks products that match the user's recent browsing patterns higher than products with no browsing signal.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is algorithm weighting logic within the ranker itself (single function/object boundary). Real failure can be caught by deterministic scoring inputs and expected ordering. Higher levels rejected because behavior text targets ranking rule correctness, not cross-module infra, OS/network, or AI model non-determinism.","test_description":"Directly test ranking/scoring function with synthetic feature vectors where browsing-signal differs and assert browsing-matched products score/order above no-signal products.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Pagination returns the correct page of results, with stable ordering — requesting page 2 twice returns identical results if the underlying data hasn't changed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Stability failure usually emerges from interaction of sorter + paginator + data access ordering (MOCK-MISS). Unit-testing paginator alone can miss nondeterministic upstream ordering. System rejected because behavior text is about unchanged underlying data and repeated requests, not real network/OS effects. No AI dependency.","test_description":"Use in-process repository fixture with fixed dataset; call recommendation endpoint/service twice for page 2 under identical state and assert identical item IDs/order plus correct page boundaries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The recommendation algorithm surfaces at least one product from a category the user hasn't browsed before (serendipity requirement), avoiding a filter bubble.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Serendipity here is enforced by diversification logic interacting with candidate generation/history filters; failures can occur when one stage removes all novel-category candidates. Not Agentic: behavior describes deterministic recommender rule, not LLM/model-output judgment variability. Not System: no real OS/network/subprocess requirement in text.","test_description":"Construct catalog + user-history fixtures where high-score candidates are all previously browsed categories; run full in-process ranking/diversification pipeline and assert at least one top-N result is from an unseen category.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A new user with no purchase or browsing history receives recommendations based on overall popularity rather than an empty result set.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Cold-start fallback is orchestration between profile-state detection and popularity source; single-function tests can miss wiring failures where fallback is never invoked. System rejected because behavior does not require real external infra; Agentic rejected because popularity fallback is deterministic business logic.","test_description":"Invoke recommender with empty user-history fixture and populated popularity stats fixture; assert non-empty output and that ranking corresponds to popularity-based candidates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Click tracking records the correct product ID, position in the list, and timestamp for each recommendation the user interacts with.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is between recommendation response context and tracking write path (ID/position propagation + timestamp capture). Unit tests of tracking formatter alone can miss wrong field handoff. System rejected because this can be validated with in-process DB/event sink and controlled clock; no real network/OS primitive needed. No AI dependency.","test_description":"Serve recommendations, simulate click on a known position, and assert persisted tracking record contains exact product ID, list position, and expected timestamp from injected clock.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The response time for generating recommendations stays under 200ms for a catalog of 100,000 products.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a performance/SLA behavior dependent on real process/runtime characteristics (CPU, memory, query execution, possible I/O). In-process mocks can hide latency hotspots (MOCK-HIDE), so Integration is too low. No AI-model quality requirement, so Agentic/Workflow are disqualified.","test_description":"Run end-to-end recommendation generation in a production-like runtime against a real 100k-product dataset and measure p95 (or specified metric) latency, asserting it remains under 200ms.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"When a recommended product is purchased by the user, the recommendation algorithm deprioritizes it in subsequent requests.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure occurs across modules: purchase event/state update must feed back into ranking features for subsequent requests. Unit test of ranker alone can miss pipeline handoff or stale-state issues. System rejected because behavior can be validated with local in-process stores/event handling; no explicit real OS/network dependency. No AI dependence.","test_description":"Generate initial recommendations, record purchase of one recommended product, then request recommendations again and assert that product’s rank drops (or is excluded) per rule.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"The recommendation results are deterministic for the same user state — requesting recommendations twice with no intervening user activity returns the same ranked list.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Determinism risk is at pipeline orchestration level (feature extraction, tie-breaking, sort stability, cache/state reuse), not just one function. Unit tests may miss nondeterminism introduced when modules combine. System rejected because behavior text constrains same user state/no activity and does not require real network/OS primitives. Agentic rejected because no real AI model nondeterminism is involved.","test_description":"With fixed user/profile/catalog fixtures and seeded randomness, call full recommender service twice under identical state and assert identical ranked IDs/order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
